{{Unclear citation style|date=August 2018}}[[Image:Cavity wall.JPG|thumb|right|A typical cavity wall with insulation during construction.]]
'''Cavity walls''' consist of two "skins" separated by a hollow space (cavity).<ref>"Cavity" def. 4. ''Oxford English Dictionary'' Second Edition on CD-ROM (v. 4.0) © Oxford University Press 2009</ref> The skins are commonly [[masonry]], such as brick or concrete block. Masonry is an [[Absorption (chemistry)|absorbent]] material, and therefore will slowly draw rainwater or even humidity into the wall, as well as from the inside of the house as from outside. The cavity serves as a way to drain water back out through [[weep]] holes at the base of the wall system or above windows. The weep holes allow wind to create an air stream through the cavity and the stream removes evaporated water from the cavity to the outside. Usually weep holes are created by intentionally leaving several vertical joints, also open head joints, open about two meters apart at the base of in every story. Weep holes are also placed above windows to prevent [[dry rot]] of a wooden window frame. A cavity wall with masonry as both inner and outer skins is more commonly referred to as a double [[wythe]] masonry wall.<ref>Matthys, John H.. ''Masonry: components to assemblages''. Philadelphia, PA: ASTM, 1990. 175. Print.</ref>
== History == The typical cavity wall method of construction was introduced in Northwest Europe during the 19th century and gained widespread use from the 1920s. In some early examples stones were used to [[Tie (cavity wall)|tie]] the two leaves of the cavity wall together,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.aecb.net/forum/index.php?topic=561.0 |title=AECB Forum : Victorian cavity wall thread |access-date=2006-12-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928060407/http://www.aecb.net/forum/index.php?topic=561.0 |archive-date=2007-09-28 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> while in the 20th century metal [[Tie (engineering)|tie]]s came into use. Initially cavity widths were extremely narrow and were primarily implemented to prevent the passage of moisture into the interior of the building. The widespread introduction of [[Cavity wall insulation|insulation]] into the cavity began in the 1970s with it becoming compulsory in building regulations during the 1990s.{{clarify|date=February 2015}}
==Advantages== *Resist wind driven rain *Insulation provided by slow moving airfilms & airgap *Enables use of low cost nonrigid insulation batts
==Tie types== * Stone * Brick * Iron - prone to rusting & expanding * Stainless steel now the norm * Plastic * Elastic
==Components== [[File:Cavity Wall .jpg|thumb|300x300px|Components on a CMU and brick cavity wall]] A cavity wall is composed of two masonry walls separated by a continuous air space in between the outer and the inner wall. The '''outer wall''' is the brick wall that faces the outside of the building structure.[1]{{Full citation needed|date=August 2018}} The '''inner wall''', separated from the outer wall by a continuous air space or the cavity, is the wall on the interior of the building structure. The inner wall may be constructed of masonry units such as concrete block, structural clay, brick or in some other cases reinforced concrete.[1]{{Full citation needed|date=August 2018}} These two walls have to be fastened together with '''metal''' ties or '''bonding blocks'''.[2]{{Full citation needed|date=August 2018}} The ties will allow the cavity wall to be strong.
The '''water barrier''' is a thin membrane that will keep moisture away from the cavity side of the interior [[wall]]. [[File:Weep hole.jpg|Weep holes in masonry wall|thumb]]
In cavity walls the [[Flashing (weatherproofing)|'''flashing''']] component is very important for the overall water management of the wall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.masoncontractors.org/2012/05/11/masonry-wall-flashings/ |title=Masonry wall flashings |publisher=Masoncontractors.org |date=2012-05-11 |accessdate=2018-08-27}}</ref> The main purpose of the flashing is to direct water out of the cavity. Metal flashing will usually extend from the interior wall through the outer wall and a weep hole with a downward curve should be provided in order to get water out. Flashing system in cavity walls are typically located close to the base of the wall, so that it will collect, on the bottom, all the water that goes down the wall.
'''[[Weep|Weep holes]]''' are drainage holes left in the exterior wall of the cavity wall, to provide an exit way for water in the cavity.
[[Expansion joint|'''Expansion and control joints''']] do not have to be aligned in cavity walls.<ref name=":2">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/43286484|title=Ramsey/Sleeper architectural graphic standards|last=1884-1963.|first=Ramsey, Charles George,|date=2000|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|others=Sleeper, Harold Reeve, 1893-1960., Hoke, John Ray, 1950-|isbn=0471348163|edition=10th|location=New York|oclc=43286484}}</ref>
In modern cavity wall construction, '''cavity [[R-value (insulation)|insulation]]''' is typically added. This construction makes possible to add a continuous insulation layer in between the two [[wythe]]s and, vertically, through the slabs, which minimizes [[Thermal bridge|thermal bridges.]]<ref name=":2" />
==Wall issues==
Breathing Performance: Early cavity wall buildings are structures that exchange moisture readily with the indoor and outdoor environment. Materials used in repairs must be selected with care so they do not affect the breathing performance of the materials.[4]{{Full citation needed|date=August 2018}}
Cavity wall insulation installed in older buildings can create problems with moisture retention. [4]{{Full citation needed|date=August 2018}}
[[Thermal mass]] cavity walls are thick walls. These help stabilize the interior environment of a building better that the thinner modern walls.[4]{{Full citation needed|date=August 2018}}
Environmental Influences: The orientation or design of a building may affect the performance of different façades on a building. Some walls may receive more rainwater and wind than others depending in their orientation or protection to some of the faces. [4]{{Full citation needed|date=August 2018}}
[[Damp]]: Moisture is one of the main problems in materials weathering. [4]{{Full citation needed|date=August 2018}}
