{{About|the curator, photographer and writer|the child actor|David Alan Bailey}} [[File:David A. Bailey.jpeg|thumb|Bailey at the British Library, February 2016]] {{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}} {{Use British English|date=July 2015}}
'''David A. Bailey''', [[MBE]] (born 1961 in [[London]]), is a British [[British African-Caribbean community|Afro-Caribbean]] curator, photographer, writer and cultural facilitator, living and working in [[London]].
Among his main concerns are the notions of diaspora and black representation in art.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iniva.org/library/archive/people/b/bailey_david_a |title=David A. Bailey |publisher=[[Iniva]] |date= |accessdate=25 May 2011}}</ref> He co-curated the seminal exhibitions ''Back to Black - Art, Cinema and the Racial Imaginary''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://new.diaspora-artists.net/display_item.php?id=78&table=exhibitions&linkphrase=Back+to+Black%3A+Art%2C+Cinema+and+the+Racial+Imaginary|title=Back to Black: Art, Cinema and the Racial Imaginary|last=|first=|date=|website=diaspora-artists.net|publisher=|access-date=7 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://whitechapelgallery.org/exhibitions/passports-great-early-buys-from-the-british-council-collection/back-to-black-art-cinema-and-the-racial-imaginary |title=Back to Black - Art, Cinema and the Racial Imaginary |last= |first= |date=4 May 2012 |website=Whitechapelgallery.org |publisher= |accessdate=7 December 2016 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504060430/http://whitechapelgallery.org/exhibitions/passports-great-early-buys-from-the-british-council-collection/back-to-black-art-cinema-and-the-racial-imaginary |archivedate= 4 May 2012 |df= }}</ref> with [[Petrine Archer-Straw]] and [[Richard J. Powell]] at [[Whitechapel Art Gallery]] in London (2005) and ''Rhapsodies in Black: Art of the Harlem Renaissance'' with Richard J. Powell at the [[Hayward Gallery]] in London (1997) and the [[Corcoran Gallery of Art]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]
Bailey has extensively written about photography and film. From 1996 to 2002, he was Co-Director of the [[African and Asian Visual Artists Archive]] (AAVAA) at the [[University of East London]]. Until the end of 2009, he was Senior Curator of [[Autograph ABP]], and Curator of the organisation PLATFORM's Remember [[Ken Saro-Wiwa|Saro-Wiwa]] Living Memorial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://remembersarowiwa.com/background-2/ |title=The Living Memorial |publisher=Remembersarowiwa.com |date=10 November 2005 |accessdate=25 May 2011}}</ref> He is founder and director of the [[International Curators Forum]] (ICF) and currently is Acting Director of the [[National Art Gallery of The Bahamas]] in [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]].
Bailey was awarded an [[MBE]] in the [[2007 Birthday Honours|Queen's Birthday Honours List 2007]], for services to the visual arts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.direct.gov.uk/en/Nl1/Newsroom/DG_068614 |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20090204064300/http%3A//www.direct.gov.uk/en/Nl1/Newsroom/DG_068614 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=4 February 2009 |title=[ARCHIVED CONTENT&#93; Queen's birthday honours list 2007 : Directgov - Newsroom |publisher=Direct.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=25 May 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.direct.gov.uk/prod_consum_dg/groups/dg_digitalassets/@dg/@en/documents/digitalasset/dg_068588.pdf |title=HM The Queens 2007 birthday honours list |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=25 May 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611191915/http://www.direct.gov.uk/prod_consum_dg/groups/dg_digitalassets/%40dg/%40en/documents/digitalasset/dg_068588.pdf |archivedate=11 June 2011 |df= }}</ref>
